@NODE CIRCUIT "Editorial Circuits"
@TOC MAIN
@{b}Words from MGN's Gadfly Artiste and Editroid
by Dave Matthews@{ub}

This issue of MGN is an abbreviated special rumour issue. Check out the
Infobahn section for all the latest rumours from the nets. Aas I write
this, there has been no concrete news on the fate of the Amiga. For
awhile, everyone was hollering about Sony, then Samsung was reported to
have bought the Amiga while Phillips was said to have bought the CD32
technology. Now the nets report that some kind of "consortium" with 3
ASIAN companies (SONY, SAMSUNG and Matsushita?) have bought Commodore.

I hope that this is resolved soon, as even if someone does buy out
Commodore, long legal wrangles and delays will kill any chance the Amiga
has of bouncing back. Apple and the PC Clone makers continue to cut
prices, and the PowerPC Mac and Pentium systems are raising the ante for
personal computers. If the Amiga is to survive, even as a niche machine,
SOMEONE has to move quickly.

                                    ***


Ever notice how testy people can be? One of the big attractions of the
InfoBahn is reading and sending messages to people all over the world.
You can find message areas (also known as conferences, echoes etc) that
cover virtually any topic imaginable, from computers to gardening to sex
and every other human activity.

If you participate for very long, however, you're sure to run into the
seamy side of being online- the flame. A flame occurs when someone
decides that some message poster is wrong, and feels obligated to let
the online community know so. Of course, the person who has been flamed
must then defend their position, and in the course of doing so, usually
raise the ante a notch or too. You can guess the results of this, as the
messages escalate from mildly insulting to outright vicious personal
assaults.

The sad/funny thing about this is how trivial the original subject matter
for a lot of these flames is. It doesn't take wildly controversial
subjects for a heated flame war. I've seen them start over spelling and
punctuation!

It's as if being online strips the thin veneer of civility we've acquired
in order to function as a society, rather than a mob. I suppose both the
immediacy of being online and the insular quality of faceless
communication contributes to this.

Another interesting phenom on the nets are Rants and Raves. These range
from facetious fun-poking to serious bent paranoid conspiracy rambles.
I'll bet that the Infobahn leads to a whole new volume in the socio-
psychological studies area.

                                    ***

One final note, I have been toying with the idea of an MGN cover disk.
This would include more illustrations and screen shots, possibly a PD,
shareware or otherwise freely distributable program, or demo, and any
other odd thing I might dream up. Any interest in this? I'm not sure
how it would be distributed, but I'd probably charge a couple bucks for
each issue. Just something to think about.
--Dave
@ENDNODE

