@NODE NEWPRODUCTS "Hot new products"
@TOC NEWSWIRE
@{b}Flying Toasters..er...Toaster Flyers@{ub}

Amidst wild speculation at the NAB (Nation Broadcasters) convention,
NewTek announced the Toaster Flyer. The Flyer is a non-linear editor
system based on NewTek's proprietary video compression scheme, VTASC,
(Video Toaster Adaptive Statistical Coding), and is supposed to provide
excellent video compression without the nasty artifacts of system using
JPEG compression. Quality of the image can be sacrificed for greater
video storage, depending on the needs of the user.

The basic process is to record video straight to your hard drive, then
using the Flyer's graphical software, you arrange your video clips in
any order you want, adding Toaster effects, titles etc.

The Flyer also features support for multiple tracks of CD quality sound,
so it is a complete solution for the high end video producer.

Price for the Video Flyer is $3995, Toaster 4000 system not included. Of
course, you also need BIG FAST hard drives; don't even consider less than
a gigabyte.

The Toaster Flyer is expected to ship by fall.



@{b}Play it Again...No Wait, Play a New One, Sam!@{ub}

Paul Montgomery, and about a dozen other NewTekians, including <GASP>
the one and only Pipi Longstocking...er...I mean...Kiki Stockhammer, have
left NewTek to form a company called Play. Rumour has it they intend to
create some kind of "Toaster Killer" for IBM PC compatibles. Hmmmm.



@{b}Screamer Wrapped or Raptor Screams@{ub}

Replacing the short lived Screamer will be the Raptor, designed by Desk
Station Technology. The Raptor is a Lightwave renderer based on MIPS 
R4400 Risc Processors. Rather than the Screamers four CPUs, the Raptor
contains two, which still purports to be ten times as fast as an Amiga
4000 at rendering Lightwave frames. The unit at NAB was housed in a
nasty black case, resembling nothing so much as a furnace. I hate it.

Retail Price is set at about $15,000, which includes 128 MB of RAM. I
hope they put the production models back in the screamer case, I really
liked that one; not that I have much chance of being a Raptor owner...



@{b}NewTek finds themselves a little TOO generous?@{ub}

Word has it NewTek was a little over generous in the free demo videotape
department. Apparently they are in a lil bit of doodoo over this.
On the other hand, look for a slew of new products to hit the market, as
NewTek repositions themselves to keep the revolution alive.
