Review by Dave Matthews@{ub}
@{ub}
While the diehard Amiga owners sit on the edge of their seats, (and the
rats abandon the sinking ship), C64 and C128 owners can sail on, nearly
oblivious to the troubles at Commodore. After all, what has Commodore done
for the 8-bit owners lately?

We have always had to look elsewhere for support, and let's face it, even
if Samsung, or whomever, decides to buy out Commodore, there won't be any
real benefit for the C64 and C128 anyway.

So, relax, pat your trusty 8-bit, and carry on with one of the most
enjoyable computers ever released.

One good way to do just that is Loadstar. Approaching it's ten year
anniversary (think about that- ten years in the computer industry is just
about forever), Loadstar continues to publish four disk sides (about
700,000 bytes) every issue. That may not sound like much to an Amiga, IBM
or Mac, but that's a lot of material in C64 terms.

One thing I really like about Loadstar, and about the people who publish
it, is their integrity. Time and time again I've been burned by Magazine
publishers who feel that just because you pay for a product, does not
actually entitle you to receive that product.

Loadstar has a rock solid guarantee- they give you every issue you pay for!
The fact that this is such a radical and uncommon practice tells us quite
a bit about the publishing and computer industries.

Issue #119, as usual, has a mix of programs, artwork and text. Starting in
the Loadstar files, Fender expounds on practical matters and Jeff waxes
philosophical. Zero page has articles on how to convert Text between
Loadstar's 37 column PetAscii and The Write Stuff's 40/80 column screen
code format.

The continuing GeoPhytes column by Ryan Hidalgo covers using geoWrite,
as well as using a REU (RAM Expansion Unit) with GEOS. Fender also notes
that the entire line of Commodore GEOS products have been "bought" from
GeoWorks by CMD. CMD will continue to sell and support all GEOS products,
which is a boon indeed to all 8-bitters.

In the bits column, Roger Gouin, the programmer behind the Max Viewer,
(more on Max Viewer later), tells all about the C64 and its display
modes.

Fender Tucker also reviews Pogo, the new Commercial "Lode Runner" type
game by Maurice Yanney.

Moving right along to Brainware, we find Marc Walter's Word Mix, a slide-
the tiles word game, Roger Norton's History Challenge III, and of course
Barbara Schulak long running Puzzle Page, (the annual Crossword puzzle
issue) as well as another puzzle by her, Coded Crossword.

The Funware section is replete with Mystical Diamonds, a game that
entails moving marbles around diamonds till everything just "clicks
into place."

Utility Ware features Big Screen, by Jeff Jones, a programming utility to
help you make giant scrolling backgrounds for your games, and List One,
which "steps" through program listings one line at a time.

Steller Astronomer, by Frederick J. Barnett, Jr. starts off the Help Ware
section. This educational program will tell you all about those "points
of light" up there.

Steve Emsley returns with 20 more "patches" to make those pesky commercial
games easier to win:

 Break It             Hunter/Killer
 Crazy Balloon        Jail Break
 Crazy Cars           Perplexian Chal
 Dragon Hawk          Puffy's Saga
 Dragon Fire          Saracen
 Eagle Empire         Skate Crazy
 Evolution            Skull
 Flight 64            Slurpy
 Fortress/Witch King  Threshold
 Ghost Chaser         Zix

In the Grafix Ware column, we find Max-Viewer. This mighty program can
display scrollable super large page sized black and white graphics as fast
as lightning. The really amazing thing about this is it's all done in text
mode! Roger Gouin, the programmer, also shares his programming knowledge
of the the C64 and graphics. One of the pictures included is the beatiful
MacPaint Nude Woman on Zebra picture. I suppose there are those out there
who may find this picture offensive, which is yet another reason I like
Loadstar- they're not afraid to take a chance now and again.

Also included on this issue are the winners of the Loadstar Prose Quest
'93 writing contest, as well as Jeff Jones' BookMeister, a program to
make digital "books" for the 64. First Kill, by Frederick J. Barnett Jr.
is about a young man's reaction to killing his first deer. Omaha, by Wayne
Faust, is a sort of time travel story with a really nasty twist,and Babie,
by David Moorman is a story about robots. Pretty good reading. I hope
Fender and Heff continue to include fiction with Loadstar.

So what if Commodore dies? We've got Loadstar.
@ENDNODE

